The funeral rites for the spokesperson of the pan-Yoruba sociopolitical group, Afenifere, Yinka Odumakin, began on Thursday with a lying-in-state ceremony held at the Police College, Ikeja, Lagos State. Mr Odumakin died on Saturday, April 3, at the Lagos State University Teaching Hospital (LASUTH), Ikeja. On Thursday, Odumakin was laid in state at the Police College, Ikeja, with tributes from many eminent Nigerians who extolled his virtues. On Friday, his remains will depart Lagos for his hometown, Moro, in Ife North Local Government Area of Osun State. In Moro, there will be candlelight procession at Origbo Anglican Grammar School o Friday from 6:00 p.m. There will be lying-in-state at 8 a.m. on Saturday at Origbo Anglican Grammar School, Moro, followed by funeral service at 10 a.m. after which his remains will be interred at a private ceremony. YOU SHOULD NOT MISS THESE HEADLINES FROM NIGERIAN TRIBUNE We Have Not Had Water Supply In Months ― Abeokuta Residents In spite of the huge investment in the water sector by the government and international organisations, water scarcity has grown to become a perennial nightmare for residents of Abeokuta, the Ogun State capital. This report x-rays the lives and experiences of residents in getting clean, potable and affordable water amidst the surge of COVID-19 cases in the state.  PHOTOS: Burial rites for Afenifere spokesman, Yinka Odumakin, begin Selfies, video calls and Chinese documentaries: The things you’ll meet onboard Lagos-Ibadan train The Lagos-Ibadan railway was inaugurated recently for a full paid operation by the Nigerian Railway Corporation after about a year of free test-run. Our reporter joined the train to and fro Lagos from Ibadan and tells his experience in this report… PHOTOS: Burial rites for Afenifere spokesman, Yinka Odumakin, begin [ICYMI] Lekki Shootings: Why We Lied About Our Presence — General Taiwo The Lagos State Judicial Panel of Inquiry probing the killings at Lekki Toll Gate, on Saturday resumed